	<tr>
		
			<td colspan="2" bgcolor="#DEDACB" background="http://www.everlore.com/gimages/tb_beige.gif">
		
				<font face="verdana" size="2" color="black">
				Here's something to help all of you out there who have been looking for ACCURATE information on the necromancer pet spells after level 50.  The pet spells are as follows:<BR>
<BR>
Level 49 - &quot;Invoke Death&quot;<BR>
Approx. 2000 hitpoints<BR>
Best possible attack with this pet:<BR>
Quad hit for around 55.<BR>
Kick &amp; bash in the 20's to 30's<BR>
Lifetap proc of around 20hp<BR>
<BR>
Level 53 - &quot;Minion of Shadows&quot;<BR>
Approx.  1250 hitpoints<BR>
Best possible attack with this pet:<BR>
Quad hit for around 55.<BR>
Kick &amp; bash in the 20's to 30's<BR>
Backstab every 7 to 10 seconds of 160.<BR>
Lifetap proc of around 20hp<BR>
<BR>
Level 56 - &quot;Servant of Bones&quot;<BR>
Approx.  1500 hitpoints<BR>
Best possible attack with this pet:<BR>
Quad hit for around 55.<BR>
Kick &amp; bash in the 20's to 30's<BR>
Flying kick around 80.<BR>
Lifetap proc of around 20hp<BR>
<BR>
Level 59 - &quot;Emissary of Thule&quot;<BR>
Approx.  2500 hitpoints<BR>
Best possible attack with this pet:<BR>
Quad hit for around 59.<BR>
Kick &amp; bash in the 20's to 30's<BR>
Lifetap proc of around 20hp<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
The level 53 pet is classified as a rogue.  What this means is that in comparison to the level 49 necro pet, this one has the ability to backstab which it trades for a loss of hitpoints.  The good necro uses this pet when he knows that he will be fear kiting, as the pet cannot tank as well as the 49 pet does, but makes up for this deficiency in the ability to deal more damage backstabbing.  The tradeoff is perhaps 30 to 40 percent, in that it has 30 percent fewer hitpoints, but can deal about 30 percent more damage in the same amount of time as long as the mob is facing away.<BR>
<BR>
The level 56 pet is a monk.  He can flying kick, quad attack, bash, and kick in addition to the usual lifetap proc that necro pets get starting at level 44.  This pet has improved hitpoints over the rogue, but still not as many as the 49 pet had.  A wise necro uses this pet with taunt off, and usually in group situations where there is a primary tank that deals slightly more damage.  Using the 56 pet in a group situation allows the necro to add nicely to the damage output of the group without spending lots of mana to do it.<BR>
<BR>
The level 59 pet is a warrior class pet.  It's appearance is identical to the spectres you see on the island in Oasis of Mar, or in Feerott near the spectre cave entrance to the gate to the Plane of Fear.  Why is this spell called Emissary of Thule?  Not because the spectre looks like Cazic Thule, or for any reason like that.  Simply because he is a representative of the god of Fear, similar to the spectres that guard the cave entrance to his portal.  This pet and it's appearance belong to the necro class for two reasons:  necromancers typically worship evil aligned gods, and the necromancer's essence is that of being a master of death.  What better than a spectre to embody the servant of such a master?<BR>
<BR>
Even though this pet LOOKS like a spectre, it's capabilities are not quite the same.  If a level 59 or 60 necromancer conjured up this pet, it would quite easily tank and kill an ordinary spectre without any intervention from the necro.  If you've ever seen someone with a spectre pet that slices in the 90's, it is not a summoned Emissary of Thule, but rather a CHARMED spectre that someone picked up somewhere and tried to scare people with.  Not the real thing.  The 59 pet is also the toughest of all the pets, being of a warrior class, meaning it will dish out the most total damage before it gets killed.  However, it does not deal out damage quite as fast as the monk pet, and as long as you have something else in your group to taunt off your pet, the monk is the preferred choice due to how fast his damage adds up.<BR>
<BR>
I have personally seen this spell drop off the following mobs, and note, these are ONLY a grand total of 3 mobs that I've seen because this spell is a quite rare drop.  I'm sure there are many other creatures in this game that will drop this spell, all of which are surely the very tough mobs that require a minimum of 1 group to kill, if not as many as 6.<BR>
<BR>
Creatures that have dropped &quot;Emissary of Thule&quot;:  Woushi, dragon guarding druid ring in Kunark.  An Ancient Wyvern, virtually spell-resistant lvl 60 mob in Skyfire.  Trakanon, poison dragon in Sebilis.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
As far as buffing necro pets go, the spells that belong to the necro class such as Augment Death, or Augmentation of Death do a good job increasing the capabilities of the standard pet, though some might look at it as the pet starting off rather wimpy then getting buffed up to average.  Other buffs like haste, strength, regen, etc. will also work on pets, and increase their capabilities.  However, the maximum hit a pet can hit for will NEVER increase, no matter what strength buffs you use or what weapons you give them.<BR>
<BR>
Weapon procs are a different story.  If you give your pet a gnoll hide lariat, you will enable him to stun the mob.  Or any other special proc a weapon has will come into effect with the pet.  But as a general rule, it's usually a senseless waste giving a pet anything except in special circumstances as the weapon will be destroyed and it will not aid the pet in ANY WAY except to impress the noobs with a dual-wielding brown skeleton.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
As far as the usefulness of any of these pets is considered, it depends on what you're fighting.<BR>
<BR>
As I stated earlier, each class has it's uses depending on the situation as stated above.<BR>
<BR>
If you're fighting a dragon?  Hmm... there's a dilemma.  Dragons, Gods, and so many other creatures that are &quot;level 55+&quot; are actually so very much harder to kill than your &quot;ordinary&quot; level 55 mob.  Most dragon roar spells will send a pet off into a corner (also known as a Fear spell) making the pet useless.  If you're lucky and the pet is there to deal damage to the high mobs, it isn't greatly significant considering these things can have HUNDREDS OF THOUSANDS of hitpoints, but I'm sure there are cases where that extra tiny bit did make the difference between the dragon beating the hell out of everyone, or a narrow victory for the guild.<BR>
<BR>
Oh, and a few more things -  These pets do NOT fear.  If you see them casting something that looks like a fear spell, that is actually their lifetap that they proc randomly.  It is a tiny lifetap, only perhaps 20 hitpoints, but part of the pet nonetheless.  And as far as necros using pets in dungeon settings, that's a difficult task.  Verant's programmers weren't intelligent enough to program the game so that the pet could have sense enough to run around corners to keep up with the necro as he ventured further in the dungeon, nor do the pets have sense not to run off out of sight chasing an almost-dead mob.  Fear-kiting is not done in dungeons either, because of the previously mentioned mindlessness of the pets, and the fact that there is far too little room.  A pet in a dungeon is an add-on damage dealer to a group if used.  The greatest use I have pets for in a dungeon is to have them around in case i get attacked.  The pet jumps in on the attacker, and I have a much better chance at staying alive.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
Anonymous Warlock<BR>
Proud member of the most modest<BR>
And best guild on any server  =)
				</font>
			</td>

	</tr>
	
